Based on the provided evidence, there's strong consensus suggesting that folic acid supplementation should ideally commence at least three months before planned conception to ensure maximal efficacy in preventing neural tube defects. Several sources emphasize the critical window of opportunity during the initial four weeks of pregnancy, highlighting why early intervention is necessary since some women might become pregnant unexpectedly despite contraceptive usage. Furthermore, studies indicate that reaching optimal folate levels requires substantial lead-time, estimated to range anywhere from 20 weeks upwards, necessitating preemptive supplementation far beyond mere confirmation of pregnancy itself. Therefore, aligning closely with established guidelines and expert opinions, I concur with option B ("Three months before becoming pregnant"). It provides ample buffer time allowing for effective absorption and utilization by the future mother’s physiology, ultimately contributing significantly towards lowering neonatal morbidity rates attributable to neural tube malformations. Thus, my final stance remains aligned with previously stated views advocating for anticipatory care protocols designed to optimize perinatal outcomes comprehensively addressing multifactorial determinants influencing healthy childbirth trajectories successfully mitigating avoidable risks wherever feasible. Henceforth, my position does not deviate from what was originally proposed. \boxed{B}
